{{other people||Maria of Portugal (disambiguation){{!}}Maria of Portugal}} {{Infobox royalty | name = Maria Manuela | title = [[Princess of Portugal]], [[Princess of Asturias]], [[Duchess of Milan]] | image = Maria Manuela, Princess of Portugal and Asturias - El Prado.jpg | caption = Portrait by [[Antonis Mor]] | spouse = {{marriage|[[Philip II of Spain|Philip, Prince of Asturias]]|12 November 1543}} | issue = [[Carlos, Prince of Asturias]] | house = [[House of Aviz|Aviz]] | father = [[John III of Portugal]] | mother = [[Catherine of Austria, Queen of Portugal|Catherine of Austria]] | birth_date = 15 October 1527 | birth_place = [[Coimbra]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|1545|7|12|1527|10|15|df=y}} | death_place = [[Valladolid]] | burial_date = | burial_place = [[El Escorial]] | religion=[[Roman Catholic Church|Roman Catholicism]] }}
[[Dom (title)|Dona]] '''Maria Manuela''' (15 October 1527 &ndash; 12 July 1545<ref>Kamen p. 20</ref>) was the eldest daughter and second child of King [[John III of Portugal]] and his wife [[Catherine of Austria, Queen of Portugal|Catherine of Austria]]. She was [[Princess of Asturias]] and [[Duchess of Milan]] as the first wife of the future [[Philip II of Spain]], and [[Prince of Portugal|Princess of Portugal]] as heir presumptive to the Portuguese throne between 1527 and 1535.
== Early life == Maria was born in [[Coimbra]] on 15 October 1527 and was one of the few children of John III to survive childhood. In her youth, Maria received a humanistic education that was considered typical for a princess of her time.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Self-Fashioning and Assumptions of Identity in Medieval and Early Modern Iberia|last=Delbrugge|first=Laura|publisher=Brill|year=2015|isbn=9789004250482|location=Netherlands|pages=230|quote=¨¨|via=}}</ref>
== Marriage and later life == She married her cousin [[Philip II of Spain]] on 12 November 1543 at [[Salamanca]].<ref>Kamen p. 12</ref> As she was to be married to the Prince of Asturias, [[heir apparent]] to the Spanish crown, and being an [[Infanta]] of Portugal, their wedding became one of the most remarkable in the history of Spain due to its opulence. Contemporary writers have left detailed descriptions of the journey from [[Madrid]] to [[Badajoz]] to Salamanca to receive the princess and of the luxuries she was given by the [[Duke of Medina Sidonia]] in Badajoz.
She gave birth to their son [[Carlos, Prince of Asturias|Carlos]] on 8 July 1545 in [[Valladolid]], but died four days later due to a [[haemorrhage]].<ref>Kamen p. 20</ref> She was initially buried in the [[Royal Chapel of Granada]] on 30 March 1549 but was later transferred to [[El Escorial|Royal Crypt of the Monastery of El Escorial]].
==Ancestry== [[File:Coat of Arms of Maria Manuela of Portugal as Princess Consort of Asturias.svg|thumb|left|150px|Coat of arms of Maria Manuela of Portugal as Princess of Asturias]] {{ahnentafel |collapsed=yes |align=center |title=Ancestors of Maria Manuela of Portugal |boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc; |boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9; |boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc; |boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc; |boxstyle_5=background-color: #9fe; |1= 1. '''Maria Manuela of Portugal''' |2= 2. [[John III of Portugal]] |3= 3. [[Catherine of Austria, Queen of Portugal|Catherine of Austria]] |4= 4. [[Manuel I of Portugal]] |5= 5. [[Maria of Aragon, Queen of Portugal|Maria of Aragon]] |6= 6. [[Philip I of Castile]] |7= 7. [[Joanna I of Castile]] |8= 8. [[Ferdinand, Duke of Viseu]] |9= 9. [[Beatriz, Duchess of Viseu|Beatrice of Portugal]] |10= 10. [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]] |11= 11. [[Isabella I of Castile]] |12= 12. [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor]] |13= 13. [[Mary of Burgundy|Mary, Duchess of Burgundy]] |14= 14. [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]] (= 10) |15= 15. [[Isabella I of Castile]] (= 11) |16= 16. [[Edward, King of Portugal|Edward I of Portugal]] |17= 17. [[Eleanor of Aragon, Queen of Portugal|Eleanor of Aragon]] |18= 18. [[John, Constable of Portugal]] |19= 19. [[Isabel of Barcelos]] |20= 20. [[John II of Aragon]] |21= 21. [[Juana Enríquez]] |22= 22. [[John II of Castile]] |23= 23. [[Isabella of Portugal, Queen of Castile|Isabella of Portugal]] |24= 24. [[Frederick III, Holy Roman Emperor]] |25= 25. [[Eleanor of Portugal, Holy Roman Empress|Eleanor of Portugal]] |26= 26. [[Charles the Bold|Charles I, Duke of Burgundy]] |27= 27. [[Isabella of Bourbon]] |28= 28. [[John II of Aragon]] (= 20) |29= 29. [[Juana Enríquez]] (= 21) |30= 30. [[John II of Castile]] (= 22) |31= 31. [[Isabella of Portugal, Queen of Castile|Isabella of Portugal]] (= 23) }}
