{{Infobox person | name = Ramon Zamora | image = Ramon_Zamora.jpg | image_size = | caption = | birthname = Ramon Artiaga Zamora | birth_date = {{Birth date|1935|6|27|mf=y}} | birth_place = [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan, Rizal]], [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Philippine Islands]] | death_date = {{death date and age|2007|8|26|1935|6|27|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Antipolo City]], [[Philippines]] | death_cause = [[Myocardial infarction]] <ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=AX3GCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA418&dq=Ramon+Zamora+died&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiPlNGJvqXdAhXC6J8KHYXEAmkQ6AEILjAB#v=onepage&q=Ramon%20Zamora%20died&f=false</ref> | othername = | occupation = [[Philippines|Filipino]] comedian and action film actor | yearsactive = 1971 - 2007 }}
'''Ramon Artiaga Zamora''' (June 27, 1935 — August 26, 2007) was a Filipino [[actor|film actor]] best known for his leading roles in local [[martial arts]] films and action movies of the 1970s. He was popularly dubbed as the "[[Bruce Lee]] of the Philippines".<ref name=GMA>{{cite web| last =Meruenas| first =Mark| title =Ramon Zamora, Pinoy 'Bruce Lee,' dies at 72|publisher = [[GMA News and Public Affairs|GMANews.TV]]| date = 2007-08-27|url =http://www.gmanews.tv/story/57828/Ramon-Zamora-Pinoy-Bruce-Lee-dies-at-72| accessdate = 2007-12-29}}</ref><ref name=INQ>{{cite web|last=Cruz |first=Marinel |title=RP’s Bruce Lee was ‘very tired’ |publisher=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=2007-08-29 |url=http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/entertainment/entertainment/view_article.php?article_id=85436 |accessdate=2007-12-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120921175902/http://showbizandstyle.inquirer.net/entertainment/entertainment/view_article.php?article_id=85436 |archivedate=2012-09-21 |df= }}</ref>
==Early career== Zamora was born in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan, Rizal]].<ref name=ccp>{{cite encyclopedia |author= Rosalinda Galang |editor=[[Nicanor Tiongson]] |encyclopedia=CCP Encyclopedia of Philippine Art |title=Philippine Film |edition=1st |year=1994 |publisher=[[Cultural Center of the Philippines]]|volume=VIII |location=Manila |pages= 338–339|isbn=971-8546-31-6 |quote= }}</ref> He began his entertainment career in 1953 as a stuntman and dancer for [[LVN Pictures]].<ref name=INQ/> He persevered in the [[bodabil]] circuit, performing regularly at the Clover Theater and the Manila Grand Opera House.<ref name=ccp/><ref name=ABS>{{cite web| last =Francisco| first =Butch| authorlink =| coauthors =| title =So long, Isprakenhayt! | work =Starbytes| publisher = ABS-CBN Interactive| date =August 2007| url =http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/storypage.aspx?StoryId=90422| archive-url =https://archive.is/20070709212017/http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/storypage.aspx?StoryId=90422| dead-url =yes| archive-date =2007-07-09|format =| doi =| accessdate = 2007-11-08}}</ref> He also was a member of the Festival Dancers, a dance troupe which performed international tours regularly.<ref name=ccp/>
From his stage performances, he was contracted in 1969 to star as a mainstay of the [[ABS-CBN]] gag show [[Super Laff-In]]. Zamora's most popular stock character in the show was a military-clad figure that bore an unmistakable physical resemblance to [[Adolf Hitler]], who spoke in bastardized German and spouted catchphrases such as "Isprakenheit".<ref name=INQ/> The role won him the "Best Actor Citizen's Award for Television".<ref name=INQ/><ref name=ccp/>
==Film star== When Super Laff-In's network ABS-CBN was closed upon the declaration of martial law in 1972, Zamora shifted gears and focused on a film career. He starred as the durable [[komiks]] character [[Pedro Penduko]] in the 1973 [[Celso Advento Castillo|Celso Ad Castillo]] fantasy film ''Ang Mahiwagang Daigdig ni Pedro Penduko''. The resulting success of the film boosted Zamora's popularity, and he soon became one of the top box-office draws in Philippine cinema in the 1970s.
Zamora was especially popular for a string of locally produced martial arts films that emerged following the international success of Bruce Lee.<ref name=ccp/> Patterning his film persona around a Bruce Lee-type with a comedic twist,<ref name=ABS/> Zamora starred in such films as ''Shadow of the Dragon'' (1973), ''Cobra at Lawin'' (1973), ''Game of Death'' (1974), ''Return of the Dragon'' (1977), and ''Bruce Liit'' (1978).
Then he played his villain role as [[Edu Manzano]]'s right-hand man to [[Lito Lapid]] in an action packed movie ''Hindi Palulupig'' (1989)
==Later years== By the 1980s, Zamora's career as a leading man petered out, and he returned to guest-starring in television programs, often in his "Hitler" guise. He also portrayed character roles in films, including one in the 1994 update of the Pedro Penduko saga now starring [[Janno Gibbs]], ''Ang Pagbabalik ni Pedro Penduko''. At the time of his death from a [[heart attack]] in his [[Antipolo City]] home, Zamora had completed one last film that had yet to be released, ''Ataul for Rent''.<ref name=ABS/>
