'''Stercomata''' are pellets of waste material{{fact|date=August 2017}} accumulated in some species of [[foraminifera]] and [[testate amoebae]]{{fact|date=August 2017}}. The pellets consist largely of [[clay]] minerals and are believed to be derived from ingested sediment{{fact|date=August 2017}}, indicating that the stercomata-bearing foraminifera are filter-feeders{{fact|date=August 2017}}, although it is possible that they may capture suspended particles{{fact|date=August 2017}}.<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cobtqd18cWgC&pg=PA109|title=Biogeochemical Controls on Palaeoceanographic Environmental Proxies|page=109|editor=William E. N. Austin, Rachael James}}</ref> In certain species the stercomata are enveloped in sheet-like formations of [[protoplasm]].<ref>{{citation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3JHpCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA75|title=Deep-Sea Food Chains and the Global Carbon Cycle|editor=G.T. Rowe, Vita Pariente|page=75}}</ref>
==See also== *[[Feces]]
